                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-defend2292" type="age" value="28"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18290910-247-off1359" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-off1359" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-off1359" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18290910-247-cd1360" type="crimeDate">7th of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-247-off1359 t18290910-247-cd1360"></join>, 1 handkerchief, value 6d.; 1 sovereign, 1 half-crown, 2 shillings, and 1 sixpence
            </rs>, the property of 
               
                  <persName id="t18290910-247-victim2294" type="victimName">
                     Robert 
                     Boyd
                  <interp inst="t18290910-247-victim2294" type="surname" value="Boyd"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-victim2294" type="given" value="Robert"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-victim2294" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-247-off1359 t18290910-247-victim2294"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-247-person2295">
                  ELLEN 
                  BOYD
               <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2295" type="surname" value="BOYD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2295" type="given" value="ELLEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2295" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Robert Boyd; we live in <placeName id="t18290910-247-crimeloc1361">Star-court, Little Compton-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-247-crimeloc1361" type="placeName" value="Star-court, Little Compton-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-247-crimeloc1361" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-247-off1359 t18290910-247-crimeloc1361"></join>: the prisoner lodged in there on the 7th of August - he was sitting in my room that night; I pulled off my apron - there was a pocket in it, in which was a sovereign, a half-crown, two shillings, and a sixpence; I put the apron on a chair, close by where he sat - I went to get some coals; he put his hand into my pocket, and took out a handkerchief, which had the money tied in one corner - I was putting on the coals, I turned my head and said to another lodger, "
               <persName id="t18290910-247-person2296">James, Henry</persName>
             has got my money and handkerchief;" he said, "Yes, he is only gone into the yard - it is only a lark" - I staid a few minutes, but he did not return; he ran away - on the 9th I met him in Seven-dials; he had no money, but he had a good hat on, a pair of stockings, and a different handkerchief and trousers to what he used to wear.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did you not send me to Mr. Smith, to see if you had left any money there, where you had been drinking, and were brought home by a man and woman? A. No, nothing of the kind - I did not leave my home.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-247-person2297">
                  JAMES 
                  VAUGHAN
               <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2297" type="surname" value="VAUGHAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2297" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2297" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I lodge in this house. I saw the apron on the chair near the bed-side; the prosecutor had given me a sixpence out of the corner of the handkerchief where the sovereign and silver was; to fetch a pot of beer, about half-past ten o'clock, and then the prisoner took the handkerchief and went towards the yard - he made his escape, and never returned till we found him in Great Earl-street on the Wednesday.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-247-person2298">
                  FRANCIS 
                  MACE
               <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2298" type="surname" value="MACE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2298" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2298" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took up the prisoner. I found half a crown and some halfpence on him, a good second-hand hat on his head, and the trousers he has on.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I solemnly assure you I went to Bartholomew-fair with this woman's husband - he told me she was in the habit of taking all his money and valuables, wasting them, and then coming back to her old quarters; when he returned home that night he found her drinking in a gin-shop with her daughter - after I got home he chastised her, and then they went to bed with the witness; her clothes were in a chair by the bed-side- I heard some one touch the clothes, and her husband rose up and said, "Henry, Ellen is off;" he dressed himself and went out; he returned in the morning, and said he had found her in a watch-box with the watchman, and she had been circulating scandalous reports, which I do not choose to repeat - she came home; her husband and this man gave her a beating; she then desired me to go to the house of a person named Smith, to inquire if she had left any money there - I left the house without knowing any thing of the money; the trousers I have on were given me by a friend, and the hat I exchanged for an old one.</p>

               <p>Prisoner to 
               <persName id="t18290910-247-person2299">
                  ROBERT 
                  BOYD
               <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2299" type="surname" value="BOYD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2299" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-person2299" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. Have you not stated that your wife has often left you, and that you found her and her daughter drinking after you returned from Bartholomew-fair? A. No, I did not; I did not see you after I entered the fair - we were going to have some supper when you came home; I found my wife at home - I did not return with any man and woman.</p>
               <p>Q. Were not you, your wife, Sullivan and his wife, drinking in Smith's wine vaults that morning? A. No.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290910-247-verdict1362" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-247-verdict1362" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 28.</p>
